{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f051f74-6bae-452d-b467-2e8f585cd9ec","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Copying the trace off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't on `PATH` inside the container, the tool will be at `%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\tools\\dotnet-trace.exe`.\n- For a richer Windows-native trace (ETW), you can use **PerfView** or `dotnet-counters` first to triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`).\n- If the container image is based on the **runtime-only** image (no SDK), install the tool as a standalone: `dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace --add-source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"409d89f9-077b-4fff-9864-121f77c787be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're seeing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":445,"requestId":"6796:FBA15:A7EF695:B6E7D2E:69FD3AEF"},"id":"fa752c89-6340-4d30-8e09-245e028f22c0","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:23:05.174Z","parentId":"9c023ada-14b2-4c42-b146-772a2146905d"}
